  "prompt": "Does the government have laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the U.S. government has a comprehensive set of laws against money laundering. Here are some of the key ones:\n\n*   **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970:** This is the cornerstone of U.S. anti-money laundering (AML) laws. It requires financial institutions to keep records and file reports on certain financial transactions.\n\n*   **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986:** This act criminalized money laundering at the federal level.\n\n*   **USA PATRIOT Act of 2001:** Passed in response to the September 11th attacks, this act significantly expanded the scope of AML laws and increased the penalties for money laundering. It also enhanced the government's ability to track and seize assets used in terrorist financing.\n\nThese laws prohibit various activities, including:\n\n*   Structuring transactions to avoid reporting requirements\n*   Concealing the source of funds\n*   Using illicit funds to promote illegal activities.\n\nThere are also specific laws targeting terrorism financing.\nThe Treasury Department's Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) is the primary agency responsible for implementing and enforcing AML laws.",
